00:16:25.539 --> 00:16:30.099
The other option is to create a workspace and get your students into that workspace.

00:16:30.099 --> 00:16:34.659
When I think about creating a workspace, I think about I'm building my classroom, and

00:16:34.659 --> 00:16:42.500
the people who are invited in here are the people who are in my class, either my students

00:16:42.500 --> 00:16:46.739
or my helpers or TAs.

00:16:46.739 --> 00:16:50.979
How do we go about creating a workspace and then sharing it with our students?

00:16:50.979 --> 00:16:56.859
As an instructor, I click on new space on the sidebar, give a name for my new space,

00:16:56.859 --> 00:16:58.659
and also give it a description.

00:16:58.659 --> 00:17:02.780
This is the name and the description your students will encounter when you ultimately

00:17:02.900 --> 00:17:05.500
invite them to this workspace.

00:17:05.500 --> 00:17:10.540
I create the workspace, and then I'm going to do a bunch of prep before I actually invite

00:17:10.540 --> 00:17:11.540
my students in.

00:17:11.540 --> 00:17:15.420
That's how easy it is to create the workspace.

00:17:15.420 --> 00:17:19.339
The next step is thinking about who is going to be in the workspace.

00:17:19.339 --> 00:17:21.939
How do I get students into a class workspace?

00:17:21.939 --> 00:17:24.180
There's a tab called members.

00:17:24.180 --> 00:17:31.979
If I click on that, you can see that currently, I myself is the only person in this workspace,

00:17:31.979 --> 00:17:35.380
and my role is noted as admin.

00:17:35.380 --> 00:17:38.619
On the right-hand side, you can see a bunch of options.

00:17:38.619 --> 00:17:40.819
Let's drill down into those.

00:17:40.819 --> 00:17:46.180
The first thing that you might want to think about is how are you going to invite students

00:17:46.180 --> 00:17:47.939
into your class?

00:17:47.939 --> 00:17:54.900
Unfortunately, there isn't just yet an easy way to upload a roster, for example, of student

00:17:54.900 --> 00:17:56.500
emails.

00:17:56.660 --> 00:18:03.140
My recommendation would be, instead of choosing invitation require, where you would have to

00:18:03.140 --> 00:18:08.260
actually individually invite each one of your students, especially if you're teaching a

00:18:08.260 --> 00:18:15.699
larger class, I would recommend setting the access option to shared, but do so for a short

00:18:15.699 --> 00:18:19.859
period of time, and share this link with your students.

00:18:19.859 --> 00:18:24.099
You want to enroll them as contributors, and I will talk about what the other access levels

00:18:24.099 --> 00:18:25.699
are in a second.

00:18:25.699 --> 00:18:32.699
When I say share this link with your students, though, I might recommend, if you are worried

00:18:32.699 --> 00:18:39.459
about random strangers getting into your workspace, that that sharing is not necessarily done

00:18:39.459 --> 00:18:46.939
in a public way, so if you keep a public course website, for example, instead of pasting it

00:18:46.939 --> 00:18:52.060
there, use, for example, your course management software or a roster that you have to email

00:18:52.060 --> 00:18:53.500
the link to your students.

00:18:53.500 --> 00:18:58.260
If you don't care about who gets in this workspace at that point, then it doesn't really matter

00:18:58.260 --> 00:19:00.219
how you share it.

00:19:00.219 --> 00:19:05.300
After initial round of enrolment, this could be a drop, or it could be a couple of days

00:19:05.300 --> 00:19:12.020
if you're having to shift gears mid-semester, switch this access level over to invitation

00:19:12.020 --> 00:19:17.099
required, and then going forward, you can use invitations for any other people you need

00:19:17.099 --> 00:19:18.099
to add.

00:19:18.099 --> 00:19:22.939
Oftentimes, I might have another colleague who wants to see how I'm running things, so

00:19:22.939 --> 00:19:27.380
I might add them as visitors to my workspace.

00:19:27.380 --> 00:19:33.699
The different permission levels, we saw that my name was listed as admin, I am the owner,

00:19:33.699 --> 00:19:39.260
and I think that role admin really translates to instructor in a teaching setting.

00:19:39.260 --> 00:19:40.260
I can do everything.

00:19:40.260 --> 00:19:44.939
I can manage users, view, edit, and manage all projects, in fact, mute the workspace

00:19:44.939 --> 00:19:46.780
if I want to.

00:19:46.780 --> 00:19:56.140
Another level is moderator, which in an instructional sense would maybe correspond to a TA.

00:19:56.140 --> 00:20:00.420
The moderators can view, edit, and manage all projects, but they don't really get to

00:20:00.420 --> 00:20:02.500
manage users.

00:20:02.500 --> 00:20:04.260
Contributors are what I would say students.

00:20:04.260 --> 00:20:10.520
They can create, edit, and manage only their own projects, and a viewer, usually I use

00:20:10.520 --> 00:20:14.920
it in a course setting as an auditor or a visitor or colleague who might want to see

00:20:15.079 --> 00:20:22.800
how things are working, they can only view projects that are shared with everyone.

00:20:22.800 --> 00:20:29.640
Under the members, that same tab, we also saw these permission levels, and I would recommend

00:20:29.640 --> 00:20:31.520
unchecking all of these.

00:20:31.520 --> 00:20:33.000
What are they saying?

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:34.959
Contributors can see the members list.

00:20:34.959 --> 00:20:40.319
This is basically saying, should your students be able to see each other's names?

00:20:40.319 --> 00:20:43.599
If you think about just your students being able to see each other's names, maybe that's

00:20:43.599 --> 00:20:51.839
not a big deal, but if you are going to potentially open this course up to the public, you might

00:20:51.839 --> 00:20:58.880
have concerns about your students' names being publicly available, so I tend to like to uncheck

00:20:58.880 --> 00:21:00.959
that box.

00:21:00.959 --> 00:21:03.880
Contributors can make their projects visible to all members.

00:21:03.880 --> 00:21:10.079
If this is for a course that is graded where you are expecting that students not share

00:21:10.079 --> 00:21:15.280
code with each other, let's not make it easier for them to do so, so you can uncheck that

00:21:15.280 --> 00:21:17.640
box as well.

00:21:17.640 --> 00:21:23.400
Contributors can change project resources, so you can change how much memory is allocated

00:21:23.400 --> 00:21:25.640
to certain projects.

00:21:25.640 --> 00:21:29.280
This might be something you might want to check or you might want to uncheck.

00:21:29.280 --> 00:21:33.920
I would say, especially if you are teaching introductory students, chances are this is

00:21:33.920 --> 00:21:38.420
not going to be a concept they are super comfortable with anyway, so you can uncheck that.

00:21:38.420 --> 00:21:42.660
You can always set that level for them yourself later on.

00:21:42.660 --> 00:21:46.500
Ultimately, should viewers, like auditors, be able to see the members list?

00:21:46.500 --> 00:21:49.099
I usually uncheck that too.

00:21:49.099 --> 00:21:54.420
The moral of the story here is that you should think carefully before checking these boxes,

00:21:54.420 --> 00:21:58.579
and if you are not sure, leave them unchecked.

00:21:58.579 --> 00:22:05.819
When you create a new workspace, you, by default, can get 10 people in there, including yourself.

00:22:05.900 --> 00:22:12.339
A lot of us teach courses that have more than 10 students in it, so we have this limit there

00:22:12.339 --> 00:22:18.219
in order to keep track of usage levels, so you can actually request more members on that

00:22:18.219 --> 00:22:23.219
members tab, and I would recommend doing so as soon as you set this up.

00:22:23.219 --> 00:22:27.859
What this means is that if you are setting this up today and wanting to teach it tomorrow

00:22:27.859 --> 00:22:33.219
morning first thing, that might be a little tough because a human actually needs to approve

00:22:33.219 --> 00:22:38.780
this, so put in your request as quickly as possible and tell us a bit about what you

00:22:38.780 --> 00:22:40.619
are using this space for.

00:22:40.619 --> 00:22:43.819
We are not denying any requests at this point.

00:22:43.819 --> 00:22:49.459
This is more for tracking of what people are using RStudio Cloud for so that we can try

00:22:49.459 --> 00:22:55.140
to anticipate what the demand levels might be.

00:22:55.140 --> 00:23:00.579
Another very attractive feature of RStudio Cloud, if you are using workspaces, is this

00:23:00.579 --> 00:23:02.979
idea of a base project.

00:23:03.020 --> 00:23:05.180
What do I mean by a base project?

00:23:05.180 --> 00:23:12.780
In this base project, the packages you want installed on students' projects live there.

00:23:12.780 --> 00:23:17.979
Text documents that you want to appear on all student projects also live there.

00:23:17.979 --> 00:23:22.619
I usually use this for something like a code of conduct, for example, or if you have specific

00:23:22.619 --> 00:23:29.339
instructions that are the same from assignment to assignment, you can put in things like

00:23:29.540 --> 00:23:34.459
how do you turn in your work there as well.

00:23:34.459 --> 00:23:40.660
The base project applies to all projects created after the base project has been specified.

00:23:40.660 --> 00:23:44.459
It does not apply retroactively, and that should be an attractive feature.

00:23:44.459 --> 00:23:50.180
Once people create a project in the class, the settings of that project shouldn't change

00:23:50.180 --> 00:23:55.099
if you later decide to change how your base project looks.

00:23:55.099 --> 00:24:00.459
I think most importantly, the base project can be updated as many times as you like throughout

00:24:00.459 --> 00:24:05.020
the course without having to convince any IT people.

00:24:05.020 --> 00:24:10.300
There might be a new version of a package that you want your students to learn about,

00:24:10.300 --> 00:24:14.859
and you can choose to install that package to your base project at 2 a.m. the night before

00:24:14.859 --> 00:24:19.099
you teach, and tomorrow morning when they get in and start working on an assignment,

00:24:19.099 --> 00:24:22.140
it will be available to them.

00:24:22.140 --> 00:24:25.500
How does it work to create a base project?

00:24:25.500 --> 00:24:26.739
There are a few steps for it.

00:24:26.739 --> 00:24:30.839
You start by creating just like any old project.

00:24:30.839 --> 00:24:36.060
In this base project, you're going to want to install any packages that you may want

00:24:36.060 --> 00:24:37.060
to have.

00:24:37.060 --> 00:24:40.380
I like renaming the project right away as base project.

00:24:40.380 --> 00:24:46.300
You really can use any name you want, it just needs to be identifiable so that you can choose

00:24:46.300 --> 00:24:48.140
it from a list later.

00:24:48.140 --> 00:24:52.780
As I said before, I always like creating an R Markdown document, because that list

00:24:52.780 --> 00:24:55.380
of packages, I forget what they are.

00:24:55.380 --> 00:24:59.500
All the list of packages you need to get R Markdown up and running, at least RStudio

00:24:59.500 --> 00:25:04.420
does it automatically for me, so even though I'm not putting in R Markdown document here,

00:25:04.420 --> 00:25:07.060
I go through the motions of doing so.

00:25:07.060 --> 00:25:12.859
I like adding a plain text file that is basically a code of conduct, so I would add some verbiage

00:25:12.859 --> 00:25:17.380
to that, but to keep things simple, I'll leave it just with a heading for now.

00:25:17.380 --> 00:25:24.540
This means this file is going to be copied over to every single project created in this

00:25:24.540 --> 00:25:35.219
workspace, and then I'm going to want to choose this to be my base project.

00:25:35.219 --> 00:25:40.380
I'm showing you something here that I almost do every single time, which is that before

00:25:40.380 --> 00:25:46.619
you can make a project your base project, you need to change its permissions to be available

00:25:46.619 --> 00:25:48.939
to everyone.

00:25:48.939 --> 00:25:53.900
We want to change the permissions to be available to everyone, then we click on the gear icon

00:25:53.900 --> 00:26:02.099
and select the base project by name, and then if at a later point you want to edit it, you

00:26:02.099 --> 00:26:03.859
can actually do so.

00:26:03.859 --> 00:26:10.500
Say tomorrow you decide to teach a topic that uses a package that you haven't used before,

00:26:10.500 --> 00:26:15.819
you can actually go ahead and add that package to your base project.

00:26:15.819 --> 00:26:20.500
You can see that once a project has been set as a base project, it disappears from

00:26:20.500 --> 00:26:25.500
the project list, so now I'm creating a regular project in my class.

00:26:25.500 --> 00:26:29.859
Let's say this is the homework 1 assignment that I'm creating for my students.

00:26:29.859 --> 00:26:37.739
I can create a template document for them to start working on, and you will see that

00:26:37.739 --> 00:26:44.160
as I'm creating this document, RStudio does not prompt me to install the packages that

00:26:44.160 --> 00:26:51.079
are required for R Markdown, because those already got carried over from my base project.

00:26:51.079 --> 00:26:55.000
If this is the homework assignment I want to give, I'm going to make it available to

00:26:55.000 --> 00:27:06.680
everyone, and I'm going to check the box next to make this project an assignment.

00:27:06.680 --> 00:27:12.319
Now that I have set up a base project, and the first homework assignment in my class,

00:27:12.319 --> 00:27:15.239
it is time for me to invite my students.

00:27:15.239 --> 00:27:22.400
I go to the members tab of my workspace, I choose shared, I say that initial row for

00:27:22.400 --> 00:27:26.319
my students should be contributors, and I copy the sharing link.

00:27:26.319 --> 00:27:30.239
It's going to end up being an awfully long link, you might want to use a link shortener

00:27:30.239 --> 00:27:34.760
or something before you email it to your students, it doesn't really matter.

00:27:34.760 --> 00:27:40.800
And then your student now receives that email from you with the link to the workspace.

00:27:40.800 --> 00:27:44.079
So how do things look like for your student?

00:27:44.079 --> 00:27:48.439
They go to that link, and this is where they land.

00:27:48.439 --> 00:27:53.160
They need to log in, and they can use, if they have an existing Google account, log

00:27:53.160 --> 00:27:58.739
in, it says do you want to join this space, yes, and they land here with your message

00:27:58.739 --> 00:28:04.040
about this is what this workspace is for, and if they get to the projects, they can

00:28:04.040 --> 00:28:07.359
see their homework one assignment and start it.

00:28:07.359 --> 00:28:12.560
So you can see that the R Markdown file you set up for them is there, the document knits

00:28:12.560 --> 00:28:18.680
without prompting students to install any packages, the code of conduct from the base

00:28:18.680 --> 00:28:24.280
project is also there as well.

00:28:24.280 --> 00:28:26.880
One other thing I will mention is Git integration.

00:28:26.880 --> 00:28:32.000
I said that Git works out of the box for RStudio Cloud, this is only relevant if you're teaching

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:37.839
with Git and GitHub, I mean, in a teaching context.

00:28:37.839 --> 00:28:41.479
It's only relevant if you're teaching version control as well.

00:28:41.479 --> 00:28:46.479
I think the really, really attractive thing is that your base project templates can be

00:28:46.479 --> 00:28:53.239
used, which means that when students go and clone a new project from Git, they will get

00:28:53.239 --> 00:28:59.439
any plain text files that live in that Git repository, but the RStudio Cloud project

00:28:59.439 --> 00:29:05.260
that they initiate will also have the right packages installed.

00:29:05.260 --> 00:29:12.560
So they get the text files that are going to be version tracked from Git, but they land

00:29:12.560 --> 00:29:17.959
them in an RStudio environment that has the right packages with the right versions and

00:29:17.959 --> 00:29:22.359
everything you have set up for them installed.

00:29:22.359 --> 00:29:27.319
On the other side, a little bit disappointing side, at least for now, if you're teaching

00:29:27.319 --> 00:29:33.479
with Git, you need to introduce yourself to Git once per each project.

00:29:33.479 --> 00:29:38.599
That usually translates to for each assignment that you assign to your students, for example,

00:29:38.599 --> 00:29:42.160
which means that at the beginning of each of your assignments, you're probably going

00:29:42.160 --> 00:29:46.560
to want to include some instructions like one of the following.

00:29:46.560 --> 00:29:51.000
If you're happy with your students using the terminal, remember that the RStudio IDE has

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:58.319
a terminal window and they can use commands like git config username and git config user

00:29:58.319 --> 00:30:02.359
email and run those in the terminal.

00:30:02.359 --> 00:30:07.119
Personally for teaching introductory courses, I try to not land my students in the terminal

00:30:07.119 --> 00:30:14.680
as much as possible, so I like the function called use git config from the useness package,

00:30:14.680 --> 00:30:24.199
which basically runs the same thing as running the commands in the terminal, except they're

00:30:24.199 --> 00:30:29.280
doing things in RStudio so things feel a little bit more familiar.

00:30:29.280 --> 00:30:35.079
Important thing here is that if you're going to be asking students to use the useness command,

00:30:35.079 --> 00:30:40.119
you want to make sure that you install the useness package in your base package as well,

00:30:40.119 --> 00:30:47.880
so they're not going to have to install it themselves, so your instructions work out of the box.

00:30:47.880 --> 00:30:51.920
So pros and cons of sharing a workspace in this manner.

00:30:51.920 --> 00:30:56.439
On the good side, you get these various permission levels, which I think is really attractive,

00:30:56.439 --> 00:30:59.239
especially if you work with TAs.

00:30:59.239 --> 00:31:04.719
The base projects with the desired packages installed is another attractive feature.

00:31:04.719 --> 00:31:10.400
The assignment feature removes the need to remind students to make a copy of the project

00:31:10.400 --> 00:31:16.560
before they start work so they no longer get that pesky temporary project blinking light.

00:31:16.560 --> 00:31:27.280
Instead, as they click start on an assignment, RStudio Cloud automatically makes that copy for them.

00:31:27.280 --> 00:31:33.959
I think most importantly, especially for remote teaching, this ability to peek in the student

00:31:33.959 --> 00:31:36.959
projects is very attractive.

00:31:36.959 --> 00:31:43.359
On the not-so-good side, students land in the workspace and they may need some instructions

00:31:43.359 --> 00:31:49.800
to figure out what they need to do next because when they land in the workspace, remember,

00:31:49.800 --> 00:31:56.199
they see your workspace name and your instructions, so you might want to put in your welcome message

00:31:56.199 --> 00:32:01.560
something like, now click on projects to find out your assignments.

00:32:01.560 --> 00:32:06.680
The git config step that we just talked about for each project can get tedious, and I think

00:32:06.680 --> 00:32:09.719
most importantly, it doesn't reflect realistic practice.

00:32:09.719 --> 00:32:14.439
If you're running things locally, that config step is something you would probably do globally

00:32:14.439 --> 00:32:16.560
just once on your computer.

00:32:16.560 --> 00:32:22.680
I do hope that that's something that will change soon, once we have a different way

00:32:22.680 --> 00:32:30.560
of figuring out how files are shared at the system level for each account.

00:32:30.560 --> 00:32:36.119
As I mentioned, for remote teaching, now you can easily peek into your student projects.

00:32:36.119 --> 00:32:45.760
Here is a workshop that I taught remotely, and I have projects for each one of the modules

00:32:45.760 --> 00:32:48.199
in the workshop.

00:32:48.199 --> 00:32:53.560
I usually like this view in my workspaces, where you can see on the right-hand side for

00:32:53.560 --> 00:32:59.040
list projects, I only click on yours, which means mine, which means I don't have to see

00:32:59.040 --> 00:33:04.319
all the copies that my students have made, because if you have hundreds of students,

00:33:04.319 --> 00:33:09.520
that list is going to get very long, but it gives me this really nicely organized view

00:33:09.520 --> 00:33:14.920
of the modules or assignments I've given my students, and I can click on those links that

00:33:14.920 --> 00:33:19.520
says view drive projects, and I didn't want to show you the next step, because it would

00:33:19.520 --> 00:33:24.000
have student names in there, but then you would be able to see the projects of every

00:33:24.000 --> 00:33:28.920
single one of your students who have made a copy, and then click on it and actually

00:33:28.920 --> 00:33:29.920
go into their project.

00:33:29.920 --> 00:33:36.640
So, you can see their code exactly where they left it, which is great for helping them.

00:33:36.640 --> 00:33:41.119
Obviously, I think initially, you probably want to get them to describe to you what the

00:33:41.119 --> 00:33:46.640
issue is, but things can get a little bit frustrating, especially if you can't see their

00:33:46.640 --> 00:33:51.199
screen, so this is an opportunity to actually peek in.

00:33:51.199 --> 00:33:56.760
You can also see how many students or which students actually started their work, if that's

00:33:56.760 --> 00:34:01.359
something you want to track at certain points of an assignment.

00:34:01.359 --> 00:34:08.000
A few common pitfalls using either paradigm, sharing projects or sharing a workspace.

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:13.560
It's important to remember that when a student makes a copy of your project, or when they

00:34:13.560 --> 00:34:20.399
start an assignment, RStudio Cloud is making a literal copy of that project at that time

00:34:20.399 --> 00:34:21.399
point.

00:34:21.399 --> 00:34:27.639
So, changes you make after a student launches a project under either model won't propagate

00:34:27.639 --> 00:34:29.000
to their project.

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:35.399
This is not like collaborative editing of Google Docs, it is more like you distributing,

00:34:35.399 --> 00:34:40.479
handing out paper to your students, and then if you make changes to your own copy, that's

00:34:40.479 --> 00:34:42.679
not going to propagate to theirs.

00:34:42.679 --> 00:34:43.679
What does this mean?

00:34:43.679 --> 00:34:48.320
Until you're ready to share an assignment with your students, I would recommend keeping

00:34:48.399 --> 00:34:53.520
the access level to be available only to you, which is the default anyway, so you could

00:34:53.520 --> 00:34:59.120
be working on what your next week's homework is going to look like, and your students don't

00:34:59.120 --> 00:35:06.399
need to see that work until you're ready to actually make that project available to everyone.

00:35:06.399 --> 00:35:11.719
Another common pitfall that I see is that packages in the base project will be installed

00:35:11.719 --> 00:35:15.479
for everyone, but they will not be loaded.

00:35:15.800 --> 00:35:21.280
If you need students to run code in the console that requires a package, your instructions

00:35:21.280 --> 00:35:26.000
should remind them to load the package first, so run something like a library command.

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:30.439
They never should need to run install packages, unless that's part of your learning objective

00:35:30.439 --> 00:35:35.639
of course, but they do need to run the library command, and also, if using an R Markdown

00:35:35.639 --> 00:35:40.800
document that you're giving them as a template, you might have a chunk on top that loads the

00:35:40.800 --> 00:35:45.439
packages that you want.

00:35:46.399 --> 00:35:52.080
If you have any feedback or questions, or RStudio Cloud isn't working, and you need

00:35:52.080 --> 00:35:57.040
some troubleshooting, the first thing you can do is you'll see on the left-hand side

00:35:57.040 --> 00:36:05.239
on the menu, at the bottom, you'll see a link to system status, which will take you to status.rstudio.com,

00:36:05.239 --> 00:36:10.080
and there you can see all the hosted services that RStudio runs, one of which is RStudio

00:36:10.199 --> 00:36:17.800
Cloud, but also things like ShinyApps.io as well, and if things seem normal there, then

00:36:17.800 --> 00:36:23.199
I would recommend, but you are having difficulty with something, then I would recommend reporting

00:36:23.199 --> 00:36:27.600
it because you might be the first person who is actually seeing the issue.

00:36:27.600 --> 00:36:34.000
You might also see that it might be going, that RStudio Cloud might be under active maintenance,

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:39.439
or that there is an issue that's reported, and there's certain levels, and the team that

00:36:39.439 --> 00:36:43.600
works, the engineering team that works on RStudio Cloud, if there is actually an outage

00:36:43.600 --> 00:36:45.760
issue, will provide details there.

00:36:45.760 --> 00:36:50.919
So that's really the first place to check to see what's up with RStudio Cloud today.

00:36:50.919 --> 00:36:56.000
Other options, if you're having any sort of either questions about how to do something

00:36:56.000 --> 00:37:02.560
on RStudio Cloud, or want to report an issue, you can post on RStudio Community, but you

00:37:02.560 --> 00:37:06.360
can also email support at rstudio.cloud.

00:37:06.360 --> 00:37:12.159
I think the third option might be especially useful if you are an instructor, and you have

00:37:12.159 --> 00:37:16.520
to share something like a link to a student project, so that if there's an issue with

00:37:16.520 --> 00:37:21.719
a particular student's work, that the student can't get into it, that may not be something

00:37:21.719 --> 00:37:26.080
you may want to share publicly on RStudio Community, so you're welcome to email support

00:37:26.080 --> 00:37:30.000
at RStudio Cloud with that.

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:35.239
A couple things that are on the horizon for RStudio Cloud, we are working towards providing

00:37:35.280 --> 00:37:40.919
institution accounts, so this will be especially useful if you are a person who is maybe a

00:37:40.919 --> 00:37:46.199
course organizer for a course that runs with multiple sections, and you want to be able

00:37:46.199 --> 00:37:50.560
to manage them in a centralized fashion, you should be able to do that, this is coming

00:37:50.560 --> 00:37:53.239
down the pipeline soon.

00:37:53.239 --> 00:37:59.120
Another thing is a dashboard for student usage and engagement metrics, so you can see on

00:37:59.120 --> 00:38:04.000
a monthly basis maybe how many members you have, how many active projects, what the compute

00:38:04.000 --> 00:38:09.199
units are, and you'll be able to drill down into these more as well.

00:38:09.199 --> 00:38:17.000
We are also, we have a package actually called RS Cloud that is for managing RStudio Cloud

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:26.959
spaces with R, it currently requires an API key, which any instructor can request, currently

00:38:26.959 --> 00:38:32.239
you need to do that via email to support at RStudio Cloud, but soon you'll be able to

00:38:32.239 --> 00:38:34.639
do so in the UI as well.

00:38:34.639 --> 00:38:40.800
Some of the attractive features of this package is that it has functions for inviting your

00:38:40.800 --> 00:38:46.000
students to your workspace and stuff like that, so you can basically get to automate

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:52.639
some of those steps, instead of having to click around in the RStudio Cloud UI.

00:38:52.639 --> 00:38:57.520
A few parting remarks, I'll start with some tips.

00:38:57.520 --> 00:39:03.040
First of all, each project is allocated one gig of RAM, which means that you really should

00:39:03.040 --> 00:39:09.399
test things out before assignments involving especially large datasets.

00:39:09.399 --> 00:39:13.959
It's important that you give this a try, and one of the things where you may not be able

00:39:13.959 --> 00:39:22.760
to try is if you have a project that is involving students to go get their own datasets, then

00:39:22.760 --> 00:39:28.320
you can't necessarily foresee whether or not the memory will be sufficient.

00:39:28.320 --> 00:39:33.840
Remember that you can increase the memory allocation of a project if you need, but it's

00:39:33.840 --> 00:39:40.000
important to test things out so you don't run into surprising roadblocks in the middle

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:42.000
of teaching.

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:46.280
Another really important thing is that what your students see is not always what you see.

00:39:46.280 --> 00:39:51.199
Earlier on in the slides, I had the little icons for the teacher view and the student

00:39:51.239 --> 00:39:54.639
view, and we could see that those look a little bit different.

00:39:54.639 --> 00:39:59.679
My strong recommendation for you would be to create a secondary account with another

00:39:59.679 --> 00:40:06.760
throwaway email address you have, and add that account as a student at the contributor

00:40:06.760 --> 00:40:08.120
level.

00:40:08.120 --> 00:40:13.360
I would recommend logging on from that account from something like an incognito window, so

00:40:13.360 --> 00:40:19.479
that you can test to see what your students will see before they actually see it.

00:40:19.479 --> 00:40:25.239
Final tips, I think brief screencasts for getting students oriented with the platform.

00:40:25.239 --> 00:40:30.320
This is especially true if you're remote teaching, and if you don't have a synchronous component

00:40:30.320 --> 00:40:35.159
to your teaching, or you won't be able to show things on the board like you might when

00:40:35.159 --> 00:40:39.040
you're teaching in person, I think is really useful.

00:40:39.040 --> 00:40:46.199
The screencasts that I showed during this webinar are included in this YouTube playlist

00:40:46.199 --> 00:40:48.560
if you would like to borrow some of them.

00:40:48.639 --> 00:40:52.879
Many of them are geared towards instructors, but a couple of them were from the student

00:40:52.879 --> 00:40:58.560
view, so you're welcome to use those if you would like to do so.

00:40:58.560 --> 00:41:03.280
Another thing that I see very regularly is that this is what the RStudio Cloud window

00:41:03.280 --> 00:41:09.320
looks like when you first start, and many of our students work on not huge screens,

00:41:09.320 --> 00:41:15.479
but something like a 13-inch laptop or a Chromebook that's even smaller, and so the real estate

00:41:15.479 --> 00:41:22.159
is really limited, and you have this sidebar on the left-hand side, and a lot of students

00:41:22.159 --> 00:41:28.719
forget to X out of that to close it, and they lose valuable real estate, so I would recommend

00:41:28.719 --> 00:41:34.239
reminding your students that they can click on that X next to the RStudio Cloud logo,

00:41:34.239 --> 00:41:39.199
and the sidebar will go away, that will extend their RStudio IDE screen so they have a little

00:41:39.199 --> 00:41:43.239
bit more room to play with.

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:47.719
Finally, read the RStudio Cloud guide.

00:41:47.719 --> 00:41:53.600
Inevitably, this webinar is going to get a little bit out of date as RStudio Cloud evolves,

00:41:53.600 --> 00:41:59.840
but the RStudio Cloud guide that is linked from the sidebar as well is going to be the

00:41:59.840 --> 00:42:06.280
most up-to-date information on how RStudio Cloud works, because the engineering team

00:42:06.280 --> 00:42:12.959
adds to that as they build more features out.

00:42:12.959 --> 00:42:18.879
On the RStudio Cloud website on the sidebar, you'll also see a link to the primers.

00:42:18.879 --> 00:42:24.000
These are LearnR tutorials that the RStudio education team has put together.

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:31.320
These are free to use, and they are basically a companion to the R for Data Science book

00:42:31.320 --> 00:42:36.479
by Garrett Broman and Hadley Wickham, so if there are certain things that you want to

00:42:36.479 --> 00:42:41.679
offload your teaching to, to tutorials others have prepared before, you might be able to

00:42:41.679 --> 00:42:44.320
see valuable materials here.

00:42:44.320 --> 00:42:49.280
They don't actually use RStudio Cloud right now, they are just LearnR tutorials that are

00:42:49.280 --> 00:42:56.479
hosted on shinyapps.io, but they're easily accessible from the RStudio Cloud screen.

00:42:56.479 --> 00:43:04.959
And finally, RStudio Cloud is in beta, so it continues to evolve, and we are working

00:43:04.959 --> 00:43:08.899
on making sure that it's reliable and available.

00:43:08.899 --> 00:43:12.979
If you have any questions, the place to go is RStudio Community.

00:43:12.979 --> 00:43:19.060
And for now, RStudio Cloud is currently free to use, and as we learn what it costs to operate

00:43:19.060 --> 00:43:24.580
the service and how it's used by the community, there will be a paid plan available for it

00:43:24.580 --> 00:43:25.580
as well.

00:43:25.580 --> 00:43:31.139
But for the time being, it's free to use, so you can go ahead and set up your class

00:43:31.139 --> 00:43:34.179
there tomorrow if you want.

00:43:34.179 --> 00:43:38.820
Thank you very much for listening in, and I'd be happy to answer any questions now.

00:43:38.820 --> 00:43:45.860
Oh, so one of the questions says, by any chance, does RStudio Cloud integrate well with Moodle?

00:43:45.860 --> 00:43:52.899
Currently, there is no specific learning management system integration with RStudio Cloud, but

00:43:52.899 --> 00:43:59.379
this is certainly in the pathway for development, because we know that this is something instructors

00:43:59.379 --> 00:44:01.739
are going to want.

00:44:01.739 --> 00:44:03.739
So what does this mean?

00:44:03.739 --> 00:44:09.620
That means that currently, there is not a way for you to get all your students that

00:44:09.620 --> 00:44:15.060
might be on Moodle or any other learning management system used with your university directly

00:44:15.060 --> 00:44:17.459
into an RStudio Cloud workspace.

00:44:17.459 --> 00:44:22.060
But as I said, as long as you're able to reach out to them, you can share the workspace link

00:44:22.060 --> 00:44:23.300
with them, obviously.

00:44:23.300 --> 00:44:26.179
It's a manual step, but that's how you can get them in.

00:44:26.179 --> 00:44:29.939
The next thing probably is submission of work.

00:44:29.939 --> 00:44:35.179
If you are using a learning management system, it is very likely that you will ultimately

00:44:35.179 --> 00:44:39.620
want your students to submit their work there.

00:44:39.620 --> 00:44:46.379
So what I would recommend doing is once students do their work on RStudio Cloud, they can actually

00:44:46.379 --> 00:44:53.379
export out any files using the files pane in the RStudio IDE, check the boxes for any

00:44:53.379 --> 00:44:57.820
files they want to submit, click on more, and then export.

00:44:57.820 --> 00:45:04.540
That will create a zipped folder that they can upload to their learning management system.

00:45:04.540 --> 00:45:09.260
When it comes to actually grading their work, you may want to choose with what they submitted

00:45:09.260 --> 00:45:13.379
there, or you may want to simply go into their projects on RStudio Cloud.

00:45:13.379 --> 00:45:14.879
That's entirely up to you.

00:45:14.879 --> 00:45:21.419
But if you want an official record of submission, that's what I would recommend doing.

00:45:21.419 --> 00:45:22.419
Let's see.

00:45:22.419 --> 00:45:23.620
Could we download the slides?

00:45:23.699 --> 00:45:27.459
Yes, you can actually go to the link and get the slides as well.

00:45:27.459 --> 00:45:32.899
They're made with ShurEngine, so they are HTML slides.

00:45:32.899 --> 00:45:38.500
Can the student also have the workspace open when me, instructor, peeks into their workspace?

00:45:38.500 --> 00:45:40.899
Okay, so that's a really good question.

00:45:40.899 --> 00:45:45.060
I will start by some terminology there.

00:45:45.060 --> 00:45:51.020
The workspace is your classroom, and what your student is working on is a project, and

00:45:51.020 --> 00:45:53.459
it's a project that you're peeking into.

00:45:54.300 --> 00:46:00.219
Can you be peeking into that project while the student also has the project open?

00:46:00.219 --> 00:46:01.979
It actually does kick them out.

00:46:01.979 --> 00:46:06.620
It doesn't necessarily crash their session per se, but it kicks them out briefly.

00:46:06.620 --> 00:46:09.219
Let me tell you how I like using this.

00:46:09.219 --> 00:46:16.159
Usually, I don't just peek into student projects without us getting to a point in the conversation

00:46:16.159 --> 00:46:18.659
where I feel like that's going to be needed.

00:46:18.659 --> 00:46:23.780
I try to encourage students on a discussion forum that we use for course Q&A to try to

00:46:23.780 --> 00:46:28.419
describe the problem that they have as well as possible, but if it comes to the point

00:46:28.419 --> 00:46:33.479
where I feel like I need to look in, I tell them that I'm about to go into your workspace.

00:46:33.479 --> 00:46:35.300
You may want to save your files.

00:46:35.300 --> 00:46:39.340
Not that them not saving the files will be an issue, but students get worried if they

00:46:39.340 --> 00:46:45.899
get kicked out with unsaved files, so I remind them to do so and then peek into their workspace

00:46:46.100 --> 00:46:50.580
and then let them know again when I get out of there on the online discussion forum or

00:46:50.580 --> 00:46:55.020
wherever we're conversing that this is what I'm doing.

00:46:55.020 --> 00:47:00.100
Another way I've used this is actually on a synchronous call, something like a Zoom

00:47:00.100 --> 00:47:01.659
call, for example.

00:47:01.659 --> 00:47:04.379
I tell the student, okay, I'm going to go into that.

00:47:04.379 --> 00:47:10.699
It's going to kick you out, but they can actually watch me work in their project and see what

00:47:10.699 --> 00:47:13.899
changes I've made to debug the issue that they were having.

00:47:15.899 --> 00:47:18.300
What's the process for sharing data files?

00:47:18.300 --> 00:47:20.659
Just load them into the workspace.

00:47:20.659 --> 00:47:24.020
The process for sharing data files is you load them into the project.

00:47:24.020 --> 00:47:29.419
You create a new project that is going to be an exercise or an assignment your students

00:47:29.419 --> 00:47:36.540
are working on, and using the files pane in the RStudio IDE, you can upload any files

00:47:36.540 --> 00:47:40.060
directly into there.

00:47:40.060 --> 00:47:41.620
File size constraints.

00:47:41.620 --> 00:47:47.459
I think the issue more so than file size constraints is the memory.

00:47:47.459 --> 00:47:53.699
You may want to think about not just your data file size, but what you're going to be

00:47:53.699 --> 00:47:55.100
doing with it.

00:47:55.100 --> 00:48:02.179
If you are simply running dplyr commands, a large data file is not going to be an issue,

00:48:02.179 --> 00:48:10.899
but if you're going to be running bootstrap sampling on a large data frame with many rows

00:48:10.939 --> 00:48:16.020
and doing so over tens of thousands of times, then that might actually be an issue.

00:48:16.020 --> 00:48:20.659
That's why I mentioned you may want to test out what it is that you want to do in terms

00:48:20.659 --> 00:48:23.379
of the assignment.

00:48:23.379 --> 00:48:26.260
How do you load a dataset or existing files into the cloud?

00:48:26.260 --> 00:48:28.939
I think this is that same question.

00:48:28.939 --> 00:48:36.580
On the files pane, there is a button that says upload, and that's how you do that.

00:48:36.580 --> 00:48:43.100
Can we run code chunks in Python or C?

00:48:43.100 --> 00:48:46.620
The answer should be yes.

00:48:46.620 --> 00:48:52.219
It's running the RStudio IDE, so yes, you can run Python chunks.

00:48:52.219 --> 00:48:54.179
I'm fairly certain this is true.

00:48:54.179 --> 00:48:58.179
Now I have to test that out.

00:48:58.179 --> 00:49:03.899
You said that sharing a project with students, there are two main ways.

00:49:03.899 --> 00:49:08.780
In the first way, they have to make a copy of the project in order not to lose the changes.

00:49:08.780 --> 00:49:10.659
Can you show how to do this?

00:49:10.659 --> 00:49:14.899
Let's go back real quick.

00:49:14.899 --> 00:49:20.020
This is the student view of the project.

00:49:20.020 --> 00:49:22.100
Let's go to the very beginning of this.

00:49:22.100 --> 00:49:26.459
Your student comes to the project that you shared with them.

00:49:26.459 --> 00:49:31.219
They log on, and I'm going to pause the screen when I need to in a second.

00:49:31.219 --> 00:49:37.939
Over here, they can see that the project is temporary, and this is blinking.

00:49:37.939 --> 00:49:41.860
Next to it, they can see a button that says save a permanent copy.

00:49:41.860 --> 00:49:47.939
When they click on save a permanent copy, that blinking temporary project is going to

00:49:47.939 --> 00:49:49.260
go away.

00:49:49.260 --> 00:49:54.620
What that does at that instance is it makes a copy of that project that places them into

00:49:54.620 --> 00:50:02.699
their own personal workspace that I call the sandbox at the beginning of the presentation.

00:50:02.699 --> 00:50:03.699
Another question.

00:50:03.699 --> 00:50:15.620
I had a problem with RStudio Cloud to connect it to relational databases.

00:50:15.620 --> 00:50:24.100
Let's leave that question up to the RStudio community discussion thread that we'll have

00:50:24.100 --> 00:50:30.020
available for this, because I don't know off the top of my head, as I haven't tried this

00:50:30.020 --> 00:50:36.020
myself before in my teaching, so I'm going to hold off on answering the question about

00:50:36.020 --> 00:50:41.899
using RStudio Cloud and relational databases.

00:50:41.899 --> 00:50:42.899
Another question.

00:50:42.899 --> 00:50:47.139
I assume the students can download files locally, as typically they will need to submit assignments

00:50:47.139 --> 00:50:48.139
in the LMS.

00:50:48.139 --> 00:50:49.139
That's absolutely correct.

00:50:49.139 --> 00:50:52.739
They can download the files using the files pane.

00:50:52.739 --> 00:50:56.100
Check the boxes next to the files that they want to download.

00:50:56.100 --> 00:51:01.419
Click on more, and then export, which will export them out as a zip file, which I find

00:51:01.419 --> 00:51:06.219
is an attractive feature, because then they simply need to upload that zip file onto your

00:51:06.219 --> 00:51:08.020
learning management system.

00:51:08.020 --> 00:51:12.459
Some of the learning management systems I've worked with in the past sometimes don't like

00:51:12.459 --> 00:51:18.500
certain extensions, like HTML or R Markdown, they may not know what it is, but usually

00:51:18.500 --> 00:51:26.500
are okay with zip folders, so it doesn't matter what you have them knit their files to, usually

00:51:26.500 --> 00:51:33.179
a zipped file upload is something that an LMS accepts.

00:51:33.179 --> 00:51:37.860
Do I need a separate space for each group of students if I have more than one?

00:51:38.699 --> 00:51:41.899
I think this depends on what you mean by group.

00:51:41.899 --> 00:51:48.699
If the students are all exposed to the same material in the class, and the same assignments,

00:51:48.699 --> 00:51:54.219
at that point you should not need separate spaces, even if they're, say, in different

00:51:54.219 --> 00:51:56.060
workshop groups or something.

00:51:56.060 --> 00:52:01.219
However, if you have more than one classes that you're teaching, so these are going to

00:52:01.219 --> 00:52:07.020
be separate content for each of the classes, separate assignments, you probably don't want

00:52:07.020 --> 00:52:12.139
to confuse the students with assignments for another class, in which case you would

00:52:12.139 --> 00:52:15.540
need to have separate workspaces.

00:52:15.540 --> 00:52:21.979
Is it possible to correct homeworks automatically, or do we need to visualize students' answers?

00:52:21.979 --> 00:52:27.899
There is no built-in autograding that is built into RStudio Cloud.

00:52:27.899 --> 00:52:33.899
If you are interested in doing autograding with work with R, I think the most promising

00:52:33.899 --> 00:52:39.379
thing, and you need the student code to be run, I suppose, the most promising thing I

00:52:39.379 --> 00:52:45.500
can think of is if you teach with version control, you can have your students push their

00:52:45.500 --> 00:52:51.739
work to a GitHub repository, and you could run continuous integration tools like GitHub

00:52:51.739 --> 00:52:58.899
Actions on it to provide instant feedback to the students, or to do autograding.

00:52:58.899 --> 00:53:06.300
This is not necessarily a fully solved problem just yet, but that seems to be the most doable

00:53:06.300 --> 00:53:13.459
option for going forward on that, but in terms of grading student work on RStudio Cloud,

00:53:13.459 --> 00:53:18.540
your option is to go into their project and start working through it, or you have them

00:53:18.540 --> 00:53:25.020
submit the output file through some other means, and then you simply evaluate the output

00:53:25.020 --> 00:53:26.020
file.

00:53:26.020 --> 00:53:32.419
It depends on what it is that you are evaluating them on.

00:53:32.419 --> 00:53:39.939
It seems like we do not need to request anything if our group is under 25 students.

00:53:39.939 --> 00:53:46.419
If your group is under 10 students, you do not need to request anything.

00:53:46.419 --> 00:53:54.820
Otherwise, by default, in a workspace, you can only have up to 10 students, or I guess

00:53:54.820 --> 00:54:00.820
nine students, because one of the seats is taken by you.

00:54:00.820 --> 00:54:06.260
Another question is from somebody who is teaching Intro to Deep Learning course, and it looks

00:54:06.260 --> 00:54:14.540
like it could solve a lot of issues if we have six years to use RStudio Cloud, but they

00:54:14.540 --> 00:54:17.500
will probably need substantial computation time.

00:54:17.500 --> 00:54:21.540
Is there anything I should take into account specifically on the computation side of things

00:54:21.540 --> 00:54:23.179
in RStudio Cloud?

00:54:23.340 --> 00:54:28.780
I think this is where we come to the memory conversation here.

00:54:28.780 --> 00:54:33.340
You are probably going to need to request higher memory limits, and that is something

00:54:33.340 --> 00:54:39.699
that I would recommend that you do, is create a workspace, put some of your materials in

00:54:39.699 --> 00:54:45.020
a project within that workspace, try running through it, and see what is choking.

00:54:45.020 --> 00:54:50.820
If it is the case that the memory allocated by default, the one gig, is not sufficient,

00:54:50.820 --> 00:54:56.419
then I would reach out to support at rstudio.cloud to describe your use case.

00:54:56.419 --> 00:55:02.459
I know that we have, so that would require an increased memory limit, so that is something

00:55:02.459 --> 00:55:04.979
that you are going to need to request ahead of time.

00:55:04.979 --> 00:55:06.580
Thank you so much.

